To overcome climate issues, global leaders ratified environmental commitments to international agreements such as the Paris Agreement to lower GHG emissions and achieve sustainable development (Ma et al., 2023b). The UN further initiated attempts to integrate global efforts in lowering environmental pollutants and combat global warming (Bashir et al., 2023b). As emissions from developing economies such as China, Turkey, and India have risen higher than in other geographical regions (Fig. 1
                     ), policymakers in developing economies have identified renewable energy consumption as a policy alternative to protect environmental sustainability (Fig. 2
                     ). Consequently, researchers have focused on identifying key factors to elaborate on how renewable energy consumption influences environmental quality, especially in developing economies (Bashir et al., 2020; Essandoh et al., 2020). Despite these efforts, studies are yet to accurately determine how natural resources impact environmental sustainability. To overcome, this study attempts to monitor the role of gold and natural resources cost on environmental degradation in NIC economies. We selected these countries due to fossil fuel consumption, the largest producers and consumers of gold and the availability of natural resources. Additionally, overreliance on fossil fuels has meant that these countries are listed with the highest ecological footprints (Sadiq et al., 2022; Bukhari et al., 2023).
